Question:Apply hierarchical clustering to the data using Euclidean distance to the normalized measurements. Use Agnes to compare the clustering from single linkage, complete linkage, average linkage, and Ward. Choose the best method.

# Euclidean distance measurements are always used to create the dissimilarity matrix for all the numerical values
euclidean_c <- dist(cereals[ , c(4:16)], method = "euclidean")
# The single linkage approach is used to perform a hierarchical clustering.
single_link <- agnes(euclidean_c, method = "single")
# I'm plotting the outcomes of the various techniques here.
plot(single_link,
main = "Customer Cereal Ratings - AGNES with Single Linkage Method",
xlab = "Cereal",
ylab = "Height",
cex.axis = 1,
cex = 0.50)

# Making use of the entire linkage approach to perform hierarchical clustering
complete_linkage<- agnes(euclidean_c, method = "complete")
# I'm plotting the outcomes of the various techniques here.
plot(complete_linkage,
main = "Customer Cereal Ratings - AGNES with Complete Linkage Method",
xlab = "Cereal",
ylab = "Height",
cex.axis = 1,
cex = 0.50)

# Performing the average linkage method for hierarchical clustering
average_linkage <- agnes(euclidean_c, method = "average")
# Here I am Plotting the results of the different methods
plot(average_linkage,
main = "Customer Cereal Ratings - AGNES with Average Linkage Method",
xlab = "Cereal",
ylab = "Height",
cex.axis = 1,
cex = 0.50)

ward_linkage <- agnes(euclidean_c, method = "ward")
# I am Plotting the outcomes of the different methods
plot(ward_linkage,
main = "Customer Cereal Ratings - AGNES with Ward Linkage Method",
xlab = "Cereal",
ylab = "Height",
cex.axis = 1,
cex = 0.55)

QuestionComment on the structure of the clusters and on their stability. Hint: To check stability, partition the data and see how well clusters formed based on one part apply to the other part. To do this: Cluster partition A Use the cluster centroids from A to assign each record in partition B (each record is assigned to the cluster with the closest centroid). Assess how consistent the cluster assignments are compared to the assignments based on all the dataam

# Cut the tree into 12 clusters for analysis
ward_clusters_12 <- cutree(ward_linkage, k = 12)
# Add the assigned cluster to the pre-processed data set
cereal_preprocessed_1 <- cbind(cluster = ward_clusters_12, 
cereals)
# Setting the seed for randomized functions
set.seed(123)
# Split the data into 70% partition A and 30% partition B
cereal_Index <- createDataPartition(cereals$protein, p=0.3, list =
F)
cereal_preprocessed_PartitionB <- cereals[cereal_Index, ]
cereal_preprocessed_PartitionA <- cereals[-cereal_Index,] 
# Create the dissimilarity matrix for the numeric values in the partitioned data set via Euclidean distance measurements
cereal_euclidean_A <- dist(cereal_preprocessed_PartitionA[ , c(4:16)], 
method = "euclidean")
# Perform hierarchical clustering via the ward linkage method on partitioned data
ward_a <- agnes(cereal_euclidean_A, method = "ward")
# Plot the results of the different methods
plot(ward_a, 
 main = "Customer Cereal Ratings - Ward Linkage Method - Partition A",
 xlab = "Cereal",
 ylab = "Height",
 cex.axis = 1,
 cex = 0.55,
 hang = -1)

# Cut the tree into 12 clusters for analysis

# Add the assigned cluster to the pre-processed data set
cereal_preprocessed_A <- cbind(cluster = ward_12_A, 
cereal_preprocessed_PartitionA)
#The centroids for each of the clusters will need to be calculated, so we can find the closest centroid for the data points in partition B.
# Find the centroids for the re-ran Ward hierarchical clustering
ward_Centro_A <- aggregate(cereal_preprocessed_A[ , 5:17], 
list(cereal_preprocessed_A$cluster), mean)
ward_Centro_A <- data.frame(Cluster = ward_Centro_A[ , 1], Centroid =
rowMeans(ward_Centro_A[ , -c(1:4)]))
ward_Centro_A <- ward_Centro_A$Centroid
# Calculate Centers of Partition B data set
cereal_preprocessed_PartitionB_centers <-
data.frame(cereal_preprocessed_PartitionB[, 1:3], Center =
rowMeans(cereal_preprocessed_PartitionB[ , 4:16]))
# Calculate the distance between the centers of partition A and the values of partition B
B_A_centers <- dist(ward_Centro_A, 
cereal_preprocessed_PartitionB_centers$Center, method = "euclidean")
# Assign the clusters based on the minimum distance to cluster centers
cereal_preprocessed_B <- cbind(cluster =
c(4,8,7,3,5,6,7,11,11,10,8,5,10,1,10,1,4,12,12,7,7,1,4,9), 
cereal_preprocessed_PartitionB)
# Combine partitions A and B for comparison to original clusters
cereal_preprocessed_2 <- rbind(cereal_preprocessed_A, cereal_preprocessed_B)
cereal_preprocessed_1 <-
cereal_preprocessed_1[order(cereal_preprocessed_1$name), ]
cereal_preprocessed_2 <-
cereal_preprocessed_2[order(cereal_preprocessed_2$name), ]
#Now that the data has been assigned by both methods (full data and partitioned data), we can compare the number of matching assignments to see the stability of the clusters.

Question Cereal nutrition facts differ from one sample to the next, so it would be wrong to standardize the data here. This meant that only cereals with a lot of sugar and little fiber, iron, or other nutritional information could be considered for the study. Once cereal is processed, it becomes difficult to predict how much nourishment a child will get from it.

uniform throughout the sample. A cereal with an iron level of 0.999 may have the highest and lowest values in the sample set, yet it would still not provide any nutritional benefit. Almost all of the nutritional benefits of a cereal with an iron level of 0.999 are expected to be present. Cereals with an iron concentration of 0.999 are likely to meet nearly all of a childs dietary iron requirements. Pre-processing the data in a way that takes into account the recommended daily quantities of calories, fiber, carbs, and other nutrients for children would be the way to go. Since only a small set of critical factors would be allowed to supersede distance estimates, this would allow analysts to make better cluster judgments during review. Looking at the cluster average, an analyst can determine what percentage of a students daily nutritional needs XX cereal would meet. This information is derived from the cluster analysis. With this information, workers could confidently select healthy cereal clusters.
